Communicate Data Findings with Loan Data from Prosper¶

by Thu Trang Bui¶

Table of Content¶

Introduction¶

The Dataset is taken from Prosper data, which originally contains 113,917 entries. For each entry, the data represent the infomation about borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan, status, the amount, rate. Moreover, the data also allows us to know about prosper rating and score of the borrowers, as well as their occupation, ownership of a house, income range, etc. This analysis aims to find the most popular characteristics of borrowers, how to get a lower interest rate of the loan and how loans are allocated amongst various types of borrowers.

Data Wrangling¶

Firstly, we will import some necessary libraries, the dataset, and do some data wrangling to have a dataset of better quality.

# define the function changing listing category numeric into listing category alpha
def listing_category_alpha(ListingCategoryNumeric):
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==0:
        category = 'Not Available'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==1:
        category = 'Debt Consolidation'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==2:
        category = 'Home Improvement'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==3:
        category = 'Business'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==4:
        category = 'Personal Loan'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==5:
        category = 'Student Use'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==6:
        category = 'Auto'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==7:
        category = 'Other'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==8:
        category = 'Baby&Adoption'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==9:
        category = 'Boat'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==10:
        category = 'Cosmetic Procedure'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==11:
        category = 'Engagement Ring'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==12:
        category = 'Green Loans'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==13:
        category = 'Household Expenses'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==14:
        category = 'Large Purchases'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==15:
        category = 'Medical/Dental'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==16:
        category = 'Motorcycle'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==17:
        category = 'RV'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==18:
        category = 'Taxes'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==19:
        category = 'Vacation'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==20:
        category = 'Wedding Loans'
    return category

After cleaning, the dataset has 84853 rows in 32 columns.

Main interests in this dataset is:

  1. The most popular characteristics of a loan amount.

  2. The most popular characteristics of the borrowers.

  3. The factors affecting borrower's rating, Prosper score, and the borrower's APR.

  4. The allocation of loan original amount among different Prosper Rating (Alpha) and Term.

Prosper Rating, Prosper score, Borrower's APR, loan amount and loan term, the borrower's characteristics (employment status, income range, owner of a house are the features that will help support the investigation into the feature(s) of interest.

From the above table and the plot, it can be seen that most of the estimated return fall between 7.5% to 11.5%. Besides, it should be noted that the distribution of estimated returns is a multimodal distribution, which implies that there are many popular estimated return rates. One interesting finding is that there are also negative estimated returns (from -18% to below 0%). The reason may be these loans have estimated yield lower than the estimated principal loss on charge-offs.

Summary about univariate exploration

Original loan amount distribution is multimodal, with many frequent loan amounts. Taking into consideration that median of loan original amount is 7500USD, less than the mean which is 9083USD, the distribution of loan amount is skewed to the right. It can be confirmed in the histogram, when we see there are very few loans with the amount from 20000USD to 35000USD, and the most of the loans are from 0 to 15000.

There is one noticable variable, which is the borrower APR. Since there are two APR which have much higher counts (at a outstanding level) than the rest of the APR, the distribution is skewed to the right.

The distribution of estimated returns is a multimodal distribution, which implies that there are many popular estimated return rates. One interesting finding is that there are also negative estimated returns (from -18% to below 0%). However, there are reasons for this. May be these loans have estimated yield lower than the estimated principal loss on charge-offs. Thus, I did not perform any transformation or operations on this unusual distribution.

Bivariate Exploration¶

This part aims to find out if there is any bivariate relationship between the group of two variables.

Does house ownership affect Prosper rating of borrowers?

In [43]:
# plot the prosper rating by owning house/relating mortgage
ax = sb.countplot(data = df_clean, x = 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', hue = 'IsBorrowerHomeowner', order = ['AA', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'HR'])
ax.legend(ncol = 3, framealpha = 1, title = 'Is Borrower Homeowner?');

The above plot confirms that the prosper rating is related to the homeowner status of the borrowers. With better rating, the borrowers are more likely to have homeowner status (own a house or have mortgage). For the first 4 rating AA to C, the borrowers are homeowner. For the lower quality rating of D, E, the borrowers are less likely to be a homeowner. It is understandable since a borrower with a house or a mortgage tends to be rated better and receive better rating. However, the most interesting thing is that the lowest rating, HR, observes the same proportion of homeowner and not homeowner. Thus, it leads to another insight that there are many other factors affecting the rating of a borrower besides the homeowner status.

The above violin plot illustrates three main insights:

  • Firstly, similar to the negative relationship between credit score and borrower APR, the relationship between credit score and estimated return is negative. For the loans with better prosper score, the lenders receive lower estimated return. The loans with better prosper score are more reliable and credit worthy, thus the lenders have lower levels of risk, and low risk is associated with low return. On the other hand, the loans with lower score are riskier, and the lenders receive higher return to trade off for the risks they have to bear.

  • Secondly, this plot and the above plot confirm the relationship between estimated return and borrower APR. With lower APR, the lenders receive lower return.

  • Besides those insights, the violin plot reveals another insight: the fluctuation of estimated return for each prosper score. Although lower prosper score loans can bring back to lenders higher estimated return, they also have the most tremendous variability and instability. For instance, for the loan with prosper score of 1, the estimated return varies from -20% to 20%, a very large volatility. This volatility is smaller when the prosper score goes up. For the loans with score of 11, the fluctuation is very small and the range of estimated return is very small and always positive. It infers that the lenders have to bear very low risk of not getting return.

Some of the relationships observed¶

  1. On borrowers side:

  • Borrower APR tends to be lower for the borrowers with higher income. It can be explained that the borrowers with higher income tend to have higher financial stability and the ability to pay back the loan, hence they receive higher trust and credit rating from the lenders. Hence, they can get the loans at lower APR.

  • Loan amount tends to be higher for the borrowers with higher income. It can be explained that the borrowers with higher income tend to have higher financial stability and the ability to pay back the loan, hence they receive higher trust and credit rating from the lenders. Hence, they can get the larger amount of loan.

  • Prosper rating is related to the homeowner status of the borrowers. With better rating, the borrowers are more likely to have homeowner status (own a house or have mortgage) (e.g. for the first 4 rating AA to C). For the lower quality rating of D, E, the borrowers are less likely to be a homeowner. It is understandable since a borrower with a house or a mortgage tends to be rated better and receive better rating. However, the most interesting thing is that the lowest rating, HR, observes the same proportion of homeowner and not homeowner. Thus, it leads to another insight that there are many other factors affecting the rating of a borrower besides the homeowner status.

  • The heat map shows clearly the relationship between prosper score and borrower APR: They have a negative relationship. When prosper score increases, the borrower APR decreases. It makes sense since loans with higher prosper score are more reliable, gain more trust and credit from the lenders and thus have lower BorrowerAPR. Vice versa, with lower prosper score, the borrowers are less likely to be reliable and trusted by the lenders and have to pay higher APR.

  • Also, the better the rating/score of the loans, the lower the APR.

  1. On lenders side:

  • Firstly, the relationship between credit score and estimated return is negative. For the loans with better prosper score, the lenders receive lower estimated return. The loans with better prosper score are more reliable and credit worthy, thus the lenders have lower levels of risk, and low risk is associated with low return. On the other hand, the loans with lower score are riskier, and the lenders receive higher return to trade off for the risks they have to bear.

  • Secondly, with better quality loan and lower borrowers APR, the lenders receive lower return.

  • However, although lower prosper score loans can bring back to lenders higher estimated return, they also have the most tremendous variability and instability. For instance, for the loan with prosper score of 1, the estimated return varies from -20% to 20%, a very large volatility. This volatility is smaller when the prosper score goes up. For the loans with score of 11, the fluctuation is very small and the range of estimated return is very small and always positive. It infers that the lenders have to bear very low risk of not getting return for good score/rating loans.

  • The loans with better rating provide the lenders with lower estimated return than the loans with worse credit ratings. However, it is associated with higher risks. For the loans with credit rating AA, the lenders have to bear very low risk of not getting return as the return is always positive. The plot of this rating is only on the positive side. On the other hand, the rating HR has a very high risk of getting a negative return. Although its median is above 10%, the lenders may have a loss of up to 20%.

  • Loan original amount is higher for the loans of longer term. Whilst the 1-year loan ranges from 0 to 25000 USD, the amount for 3-year and 5-year loan goes up to 35000 USD. The median amount of 1 year loan is 3500 USD, for 3 year loan is 5500 USD and that for 5 year is 11500 USD.

Some interesting relationships¶

  • The estimated returns for 3-year loans are the most volatile in the three types of loan terms.
  • Although debt consolidation is the most frequent reason to have a loan (accounting for 62.70% of the listings), it is also associated with the most volatile estimated returns.
  • The most surprising finding is that loans for student use are also very risky with very large volatility in estimated returns for the lenders. This is unpredictable.

Conclusions¶

Firstly, let's find out the most popular characteristics of the borrowers. After analysis, several characteristics which are most frequent are:

  • Employment status: The employed are more likely to have the loan than the unemployed.

  • Income: Higher income tends to facilitate the funding of borrowers.

  • Home Ownership: Owning a house or having a mortgage can help a borrower to get the fund.

  • Good Prosper score and Prosper rating: a good rated borrower is more likely to be funded.

Secondly, let's find out the most popular characteristics of the loans. After analysis, several characteristics which are most frequent are:

  • Reasons for funding: Debt consolidation, Home improvement, Business, Auto.

  • Most of the estimated return fall between 7.5% to 11.5%. There are many popular estimated return rates. There are also negative estimated returns (from -18% to below 0%). The reason may be these loans have estimated yield lower than the estimated principal loss on charge-offs.

  • Many frequent loan amounts. There are very few loans with the amount from 20000USD to 35000USD, and the most of the loans are from 0 to 15000.

  • The most popular borrower APR are 0.35797% with 43% of the loans and 0.35643% with 19%.

Thirdly, let's find out how to gain a high amount of loan, at a lower borrower rate, and at the first attempts:

  • For the borrowers with higher income and higher prosper score, the amount of loan tends to be higher. The borrowers with lower income tend to have lower Prosper score and lower amount of loan. It can be explained that the borrowers with higher income tend to have higher financial stability and the ability to pay back the loan, hence they receive higher trust and credit rating from the lenders. Hence, they can get the larger amount of loan.
  • If Prosper score is high and the income range is high, the borrowers tend to gain the funding from his first attempt. However, if the income is high but the prosper score is low, the borrowers still have to attempt many times to get the loan. In other words, the prosper score has higher impacts than income range of the borrowers in terms of whether the borrowers can get the funding.

  • It can be seen clearly that for borrowers with higher credit score, the borrower APR is lower. Similarly, for borrowers with better Prosper Score, the APR is lower. It confirms the point that credit score and prosper score are negatively correlated to Borrower APR. It can be explained that the borrowers with higher income tend to have higher financial stability and the ability to pay back the loan, hence they receive higher trust and credit rating from the lenders. Hence, they can have higher score and get the loans at lower APR.

  • If the borrowers have high prosper score and high income, the APR will be lower. Moreover, there are more chance to get the fund if the borrowers own a house or have a related mortgage.

Finally, let's find out how the lenders allocate their fundings throughout the borrowers:

Do they prefer reliable loans with low risks or unreliable loans with high risks?

  • For the loans with better prosper score, the lenders receive lower estimated return. The loans with better prosper score are more reliable and credit worthy, thus the lenders have lower levels of risk, and low risk is associated with low return. On the other hand, the loans with lower score are riskier, and the lenders receive higher return to trade off for the risks they have to bear. Therefore, the lenders may prefer low score loans since it can bring back more returns.

  • However, those loans with low score are associated with too many fluctuation of estimated return. Although lower prosper score loans can bring back to lenders higher estimated return, they also have the most tremendous variability and instability. For instance, for the loan with prosper score of 1, the estimated return varies from -20% to 20%, a very large volatility. This volatility is smaller when the prosper score goes up. For the loans with score of 11, the fluctuation is very small and the range of estimated return is very small and always positive. It infers that the lenders have to bear very low risk of not getting return.

  • Thus, the lenders need to analyse carefully to find out the balance between risk and return.

Do they prefer longer term or shorter term loan?

  • It is demonstrated that the estimated returns are higher for the loans of longer term. Besides, we can see that the returns for 3-year loans are the most volatile in the three types of loan terms. Thus, the lenders may prefer 1-year and 5-year loans rather than 3-year.

How the amount of loans are distributed?

  • High risk is associated with high return. The mean of estimated return is highest for risky loans (longer term and for bad credit rating). The loans with rating D, E and HR for the terms of 36 and 60 months can provide the lenders with the highest estimated return, since they are very risky and the lenders must gain high return to trade off for the risks. Vice versa, the loans with good credit rating and in shorter terms bring the lenders lower return. However, although higher risk loans can bring back higher returns, the lenders tend to maintain the stability as most of the amount of loans is still granted to borrowers with good credit rating (A, B, C) rather than bad credit rating (D, E, HR).

  • For low prosper score, the amount of loan which is granted is small, mostly below 10000 USD. It is predictable because those loans with low prosper score can bring negative return to the lenders, thus the amount granted is small.

  • It is understandable that the highest loan amounts are granted to the borrowers with very good Prosper score from 8-11. However, the return for them is expected to be low, due to low interest rate and APR. The modest Prosper score loans are associated with higher return and lower amount of loans than the good loans.
